 ## Section A – Concept Application

### Question 1
S1
SCENARIO
You are building a food delivery platform where restaurant partners upload menu item
photos. The product team wants to auto-categorise these images (e.g. biryani, pizza,
desserts) using Computer Vision instead of manual tagging.

Question: Explain what Computer Vision is and how it differs from a simple rules-based image
filter. Why is a CV-based approach more suitable for categorising diverse food images than
writing fixed conditions based on colour thresholds or brightness alone?


**Answer:**

Computer Vision (CV) is a field of Artificial Intelligence that enables computers to interpret, analyze, and understand images or videos in a way similar to human vision. It uses image processing and machine learning techniques to recognize objects, patterns, and visual features automatically.

A simple rules-based image filter works by applying predefined conditions such as color thresholds, brightness levels, or pixel intensity. While this approach may work for very specific situations, it cannot handle variations in lighting, camera angles, food presentation, or image quality.

A Computer Vision-based approach is more suitable for categorizing food images because it learns visual features such as shapes, textures, colors, and patterns from training data. It can correctly classify different food items even when they appear in different sizes, orientations, lighting conditions, or backgrounds. In contrast, fixed rules based only on color or brightness would fail when foods have similar colors or when lighting conditions change.

